04434nam a22006135i 9780231542715DE-B159720190326051319.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190326s2017    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315427157 a10.7312/enge180402doi  a(DE-B1597)493802  a(OCoLC)1014331512  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0370302bisacsh 7aLIT0041702bisacsh 7aPHI0400002bisacsh 7aSOC0320002bisacsh1 aEngelstein, Stefani, eauthor.10aSibling Action :bThe Genealogical Structure of Modernity /cStefani Engelstein. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource :b18 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION: THE SIBLING AND MODERNITY -- tPART I. RECUPERATING THE SIBLING -- t1. SIBLING LOGIC -- tPART II. FRATERNITY AND REVOLUTION -- t2. THE SHADOWS OF FRATERNITY -- t3. ECONOMIZING DESIRE: THE SIBLING (IN) LAW -- tPART III. GENEALOGICAL SCIENCES -- t4. LIVING LANGUAGES: COMPARATIVE PHILOLOGY AND EVOLUTION -- t5. THE EAST COMES HOME: RACE AND RELIGION -- tEPILOGUE: SPAWNING DISCIPLINES -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex  aThe sibling stands out as a ubiquitous-yet unacknowledged-conceptual touchstone across the European long nineteenth century. Beginning in the late eighteenth century, Europeans embarked on a new way of classifying the world, devising genealogies that determined degrees of relatedness by tracing heritage through common ancestry. This methodology organized historical systems into family trees in a wide array of new disciplines, transforming into siblings the closest contemporaneous terms on trees of languages, religions, races, nations, species, or individuals. In literature, a sudden proliferation of siblings-often incestuously inclined-negotiated this confluence of knowledge and identity. In all genealogical systems the sibling term, not quite same and not quite other, serves as an active fault line, necessary for and yet continuously destabilizing definition and classification.In her provocative book, Stefani Engelstein argues that this pervasive relational paradigm shaped the modern subject, life sciences, human sciences, and collective identities such as race, religion, and gender. The insecurity inherent to the sibling structure renders the systems it underwrites fluid. It therefore offers dynamic potential, but also provokes counterreactions such as isolationist theories of subjectivity, the political exclusion of sisters from fraternal equality, the tyranny of intertwined economic and kinship theories, conflicts over natural kinds and evolutionary speciation, and invidious anthropological and philological classifications of Islam and Judaism. Integrating close readings across the disciplines with panoramic intellectual history and arresting literary interpretations, Sibling Action presents a compelling new understanding of systems of knowledge and provides the foundation for less confrontational formulations of belonging, identity, and agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2019) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Critical Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330840uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/enge18040423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542715.jpg  aPDA5EBK  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA14ALL  aPDA1ALL